commitmsg:
Standardize the viewport size before freezing.

Also start using Slashdot, a more challenging size with iframes and more images.
Improve naming, and add comments.

Save the freeze-dried markup as a file.

receiveMessage seems to work happily as an async.
freezeDry the page, and send the resulting HTML back to the background script.
Prove we can get at the page content.

Get an answer back from the content script.

We can't just return a value that pops out of executeScript() because webpack wraps our content script in a function. Thus, we can't get it to emit a statement on the top level, which is where executeScript() looks for a return value. Perhaps we could twiddle a webpack flag, but mucking with webpack tends to be a time sink.

Bring in freeze-dry instead of left-pad, and switch to ES7 syntax so we can use async and await.

We have to keep using require() in the webpack config because node, which runs it, isn't savvy yet.
Annnnd prove that the content script can use npm modules.
Extension now injects a content script into the current tab, and the content script logs a message.

Got rid of the popup. Now we have a simple browser action that logs "gone!" when clicked.

We also have a blank content script that webpack compiles.
Add auto-recompiling and reloading.
Add .gitignore and package-lock.
Clear out stuff I don't need. Add a license file.
Starting with https://github.com/mdn/webextensions-examples' webpack-modules folder, rev 416199ccf97fa683c1257e60a9da2c388f987e0f.

Add `yarn run browser` and `yarn run release`.

I can't remember these incantations.
Bump version in manifest.

Move caveat text to a place more visually pleasing and more suited to its chronological usefulness.

The use should be able to "get right to it" without reading through this fairly unimportant text, but it still might answer important questions, so we leave it in a place where they might naturally read it while waiting for training to complete.
Make toolbar-button action menu look less trashy.

Change the title on the Trainer to "Trainer", since that's what it's naturally getting called in the readme.

"Name things what they're called."
Update version history, document Trainer, and polish readme.

Add Trainer. Switch to yarn.

Yarn installs Fathom's own dependencies, like wu. npm neglects to.
Improve no-trainee-found error message.
Disable the Training page controls and show a nice warning when no trainable rulesets are installed.
Change Fathom Trainees extension ID.
Rename "trainables" to the existing word "trainees".

Remove the overlay trainable, which has moved into a separate webext so ruleset devs don't have to fork FathomFox.

This actually means we don't have to bundle Fathom here anymore.

Link to fathom as a submodule.

We're using a funny branch at the moment, and I don't want to lose track. This also lets other people build this without a bunch of instruction.
Add a missing semicolon.

Crank up the page-completion timeout.

Pages with zillions of ads are really, really, really slow!
Tolerate any combination of horizontal whitespace in Corpus Collector textarea.
Add visibility rule, which gets us to 93.8% on training corpus!
Make Corpus Collector open in the current window, for consistency with the Trainer.
Support optional filenames in the Corpus Collector.

Take alpha from background-color into account for opaqueness. This gets us to 87.5% on the training corpus.

Incidentally, it turns out that "rgb(...)" and "rgba(...)" are aliases for each other in CSS Colors Level 4 and up, so my regex is more correct than I supposed!
Move urlFilename to utils so I can call it from log() in the content script.
Fix opacity() implementation, which cranks us up to 81.3% on the training corpus!

Move initial/best solution into trainables.

We'll need one per ruleset, so it needs to be there.
Add good/bad page reporting so I know where my failures are.
Implement class and ID sniffing, driving training-set accuracy to 75%.

These coeffs now give 62.5% accuracy after fixing the corpus.

This is about as well as it's possible for these rules to do on these samples. Now we need more rules.

Move the succeeded-or-not logic out of the trainable so the content script can have access to the whole ruleset, not just a final boolean.

This will help us build reusable ruleset debugging into the content script: for example, we can run user-provided queries against the ruleset and show the results by setting the inspected item in the devtools. As a bonus, this tersens the trainables.

Replace loop with reduce in the (untested) hope that it's faster.

It's certainly briefer and less stateful.

solutionCost was upside-down. Fixed that.

Display in the UI was mis-scaled too.

Running it right-side-up (and on more pages: 4-38) yielded new coefficients: 40% accuracy.

Port in the overlay rules I have written so far, and debug a bit.

* There's nothing wrong with <0 coeffs in this raise-the-score-to-the-coeff-power world, so change randomTransition accordingly.
* Add some well-scoring coeffs the optimizer found (on just samples 9-12).
* Report new bests more promptly in the UI. Otherwise, it can be minutes till they show up.
I guess technically all this stuff is dev dependencies, since you don't need it sitting around at runtime.

Set the viewport size before training.

Factor up setViewportSize() so the trainer and the corpus collector can both call it.

Show best-so-far coeffs as we go.

Full annealer runs can take awhile, and this takes away the disincentive to run more iterations.
Report accuracy after training.
Make output look okay, too.
Style the Training page a bit. Add a progress bar.
Add a real randomTransition algorithm.
Init ruleset menu from the map of trainables.

Run tuner to completion, output the result, and get the ruleset name from the menu.

The menu itself is still hard-coded.
Remove test module.

It runs tuning error-free for 1 iteration.

* Stop subclassing Annealer for now so rollup works.
* Fix syntax errors.

It compiles without error now.

(rollup -c, that is.)
Factor out common rollup settings.

rollup compiles it now! wu bundles properly. Add trainables file. Add an async tab-training annealer. Maybe it'll even run in parallel; we'll see what FF does.

One of the problems was that npm wasn't installing wu, despite it being a dependency of fathom-web. That was keeping rollup from bundling it. Perhaps it's that I'm using a file: URL to fathom-web. At any rate, yarn does the right thing, so I've switched to yarn.

Add json() plugin to fix "Unexpected token" errors parsing package.json files.
Fix copy-paste mistake in error handler.
Bump version to 1.0.1, and add version history to readme.
Add PoC bidirectional communication from training page to tabs in the same window.
This traverses into (and bundles) node_modules that are proper ES6 modules.

Committing before trying to see why we have require()s in the corpus.js that rollup generates. Does webpack do the same?

Turns out it was "webpack-webext-plugin": "github:MarZab/webpack-webext-plugin" that was keeping the requires away. Remove it, and they come roaring back. However, replace it with web-ext, its sole dependency, and they stay away.
Fix copy-paste mistake in error handler.
Turn browser action into a menu so we can kick off the tuner.

Fix the "No matching message handler" errors when downloading using the Corpus Collector.

Basically, it was a race condition that either didn't exist in previous Firefoxes or that we were lucking out of.

Improve tabCompletion() waiter to take into account that about:blank loads first when creating a new tab.

...and then, to make things more interesting, it reaches the "complete" state. So we have to test against that URL explicitly, which unfortunately requires the "tabs" permission.

Get rid of that proof-of-concept sleep call as well. And quit testing against 'loading', which is an additional piece of knowledge.
This works.

Replace webpack with rollup.

I'm hoping rollup's dead-code elimination allows us to bundle Fathom. Fathom's references to node.js stdlib routines bother webpack, even though there's no call path to them from FathomFox code.

Move background script out of src folder. I wasn't using the compile pass that existed; I was just afraid to remove it with webpack.

Has "No matching message handler" errors, but so does the webpack version. Remove seemingly unused definition of backgroundPort in contentScript.js to try to fix that--no dice.
Update readme to be suitable, with minimal changes, as the description on FathomFox's addons.mozilla.org page.

Add icon source file.

It's in Affinity Designer.
Don't crash when freezing pages for the Corpus Collector, which has no highlights to hide.

Add a first whack at a real icon.

Hide the highlighter before freezing the page.

Now we don't end up with a big highlighter polluting our captured page.

Consequently, move the highlighter twiddling into the background script. This is an aesthetic win because now everything toggles the highlighter in the same way; you don't have the devtools panel doing it ad hoc through evals. But really we were forced to do this because we needed to hide and re-show the highlighter around the page downloading, which already must be done in the background script due to permissions.

As a bonus, pages can't trip up our highlighter manipulation by monkeypatching different code onto the DOM methods we call, as they could when we were using eval().
Update readme to acknowledge the devpane.
Improve devpane styling a little.
Present a Save dialog when you click Save in the devpane so you know something has happened.

Unhighlight the inspected element when switching away from the Fathom devpanel.

It conflicted with the Inspector panel's highlight and was confusing. Plus, maybe other panels will want to highlight something someday.

Add a Save button to the devpanel that freezes and downloads the page, complete with labeling info.

* Merge freezeDryThisPage.js and devtoolsHelper.js into a single content script. This lets us call freezeDry() from both the corpus collector and the devpanel without having to bundle freezeDry twice.
* Replace the port listener in the background script with a more generic dispatcher. Sometimes we still just forward stuff to the content script, but other times we do other things as well, like write HTML to disk.
* Move download() to its own script so we can call it in in a few different places.

Move elementAtPath() and reversed() to utils module.

Move $0 outside elementPath for philosophical reusability and practical visibility of captured variables.

Move eval'd string inside the function that uses it.

It might be less efficient on some implementations, but now I can navigate the code.

Move resultOfEval to utils module.

Trying to keep the UI code by itself in the devtoolsPanel module.
Shorten backgroundPort initialization.
Now label any inspected element, even if it has no ID. Also, label it with the label you type in!

Also...

* Rename "message" arg to "request" for consistency. Though I am conflicted about the overloading of the term w.r.t. HTTP.
* Add a wrapper for inspectedWindow.eval() that makes its return convention not require 2 nested branches to unpack.
Maintain inspected item's highlight when the Fathom dev panel is brought forward.
Add proof-of-concept bidirectioal communication chai between dev pael and a content script running on the inspected tab.

Keep going on error.

We do tend to hit some: like redirects, which throw off our messaging. When collecting a large corpus, it's best to log the error and keep going so we can get something done unattended.

Swap the position of the two controls to reflect which one actually happens first.

We scroll, and then we wait.

We still get more onUpdated events than I expect, perhaps due to the implicit injection of the content script. Add a sentry. Fix #22 for real for real this time.

Fix the duplicates once and for all. Fix #22 for real this time.

Turns out every page gets a bunch of onUpdated events, not just blank.html. That was firing off a second, spurious fathom:visitPage event, which was, understandably, doubling the save of the page. I suspect it was also leading to the "listener disconnected" (or words to that effect) errors, when the script slammed the tab before the second visit was done talking to it.

Fix Corpus Collector behavior in recent Firefoxes (like v65) of running past the end of the list of URLs and into `undefined`s.

This led to non-obvious misbehaviors like closing the blank.html placeholder tab prematurely.

The trouble is that we were waiting for a less specific flavor of update event on the blank.html page than we now need to. blank.html used to receive a single update event before but now receives one every time we close a tab holding a page to freeze: it gets an update event with {attention: false}.

Quit assuming the current freezing tab is always at [0]...

Merge fathom-trainees into FathomFox. Close #68. Fix https://github.com/mozilla/fathom-trainees/issues/8.

This makes fewer repos to clone, fewer addons to install, and fewer build processes to babysit for ruleset authors. It means a simpler FathomFox with less message passing. And it will make one fewer issue tracker and repo to stitch together.

And we already have plenty of variables called `ruleset` more deservedly which would collide. However, I did spruce up the top comment in rulesets.js, which should help orient newcomers.

Merge fathom-trainees into FathomFox. Close #68. Fix https://github.com/mozilla/fathom-trainees/issues/8.

This makes fewer repos to clone, fewer addons to install, and fewer build processes to babysit for ruleset authors. It means a simpler FathomFox with less message passing. And it will make one fewer issue tracker and repo to stitch together.

Rename trainees.js to rulesets.js.

We think ruleset authors will find this clearer. For now, I didn't rename the vars (`trainees`, `traineeId`, etc.) because having a var called `rulesets` point to a thing other than a collection of rulesets would be confusing. And we already have plenty of variables called `ruleset` more deservedly which would collide. However, I did spruce up the top comment in rulesets.js, which should help orient newcomers.
